Write two functions whose results are asserted with whole-collection comparisons, membership, and subset checks.

- `tally_votes(ballots)` returns a `dict` mapping candidate name to vote count. Normalise each ballot with `.strip().lower()`; **skip** blank or whitespace-only ballots (no `""` key). So `"Ann"`, `" ann "` and `"ANN"` are the same candidate.
- `unique_words(text)` returns the **set** of distinct lowercase words in `text` (split on whitespace).

The tests compare whole dicts (`==`), check membership (`in`), use subset (`>=`), and assert `unique_words` returns a real `set` whose comparison is order-independent. Returning a list instead of a set must fail.

```python
tally_votes(["Ann", " ann ", "bob"])   # {"ann": 2, "bob": 1}
tally_votes(["bob", "", "   ", "bob"]) # {"bob": 2}
unique_words("the cat the dog")          # {"the", "cat", "dog"}
```

